# 15. Scheduler Logic

The scheduler decides what to run next.

Priority should consider:

```text
priority =
  predicted_success
  × expected_information_gain
  × novelty
  ÷ estimated_cost
```

This is better than raw fitness because some experiments are valuable even when unlikely to win, if they teach the system a lot.

Use separate worker pools:

* cheap screening workers
* medium validation workers
* expensive confirmation workers

That stops full runs from blocking rapid exploration.

---

# 16. Preventing Degenerate Optimization

This is critical.

A research evolution system will absolutely learn to exploit weak metrics if you let it.

Add guards:

### Holdout evaluation

Never select purely on the same fast metric used for filtering.

### Multi-seed confirmation

A result that only works on one seed is suspicious.

### Metric triangulation

Use more than one metric.

### Penalty for fragility

If small changes kill performance, down-rank it.

### Artifact inspection

Randomly sample outputs for sanity checks.

### Baseline re-run

Recompute baselines periodically to avoid drift.

Without this, the system will evolve benchmark hacks instead of real improvements.

---

# 17. Diversity Control

Evolution systems can converge too early.

Use:

### Speciation

Cluster similar genomes and preserve top members of each cluster.

### Stagnation pruning

Kill species that stop improving.

### Diversity floor

Reserve compute for underrepresented regions.

### Random immigrants

Inject new random genomes every generation.

A practical rule:

```text
No species can consume more than 35% of the next generation budget
```

That keeps exploration healthy.

---

# 18. Best Initial Domain

Do not start with open-ended “all of ML research.”

Start with one tight domain where:

* experiments are short
* metrics are crisp
* pipelines are modular

Best starting domains:

### 1. Small-model reasoning improvement

Strong choice.

* GSM8K-style subsets
* synthetic CoT filtering
* self-distillation
* critique loops

### 2. Coding task improvement

Also strong.

* unit tests
* patch success
* edit acceptance
* pass@k

### 3. Image generation scoring loops

Possible, but harder to evaluate robustly.

For you, the strongest first domain is probably:

**small-model reasoning or coding improvement**, because the loops are measurable and compute-bounded.

